Winsorization

The presence of outliers in our variables may have strong undesirable effect on sample Pearson correlation coefficients, hence we apply one-sided winsorization to our data (values larger than \(x_{0.75} + 1.5 \cdot IQR(x)\) will be replaced by this value). Histograms and boxplots of the augmented variables can be seen below.

Hypotheses testing

Pearson correlation coefficient

The following table contains results of one sample \(t\)-tests about the Pearson correlation coefficient \(\rho_{XY}\) of given pesticide-biomarker pairs computed on the original data ((orig.)) and winsorized data ((wins.)). The null hypotheses states no linear association between variables (\(H_0: \rho_{XY} = 0\)) against the two sided alternative, that such an association exists (\(H_1: \rho_{XY} \neq 0\)). The 95 % confidence intervals and \(p\)-values are included.

Since outliers may affect the sample Pearson correlation and give misleading results we consider the tests conducted on winsorized data as more trustworhy.

Spearman correlation coefficient

The following table contains results of one sample \(t\)-tests about the Spearman correlation coefficient, which is a non-parametric measure of correlation between variables based on ranks and asseses monotonic relationship between variables, not just a linear relationship. The stated hypotheses were analogous to the previous case, but Spearman correlation is robust to outliers and violations of normality. 95 % confidence intervals based on Z-transformation and \(p\)-values are included.
